# 03 — Skills & Observability

## SKILL FILE PROTOCOL

Skills are Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) for Cursor.
They turn repeatable tasks into consistent, step-by-step processes executed the same way every time.

### When to Create a Skill
```
✓ Task has more than 5 steps
✓ Task is done more than once
✓ Missing a step causes bugs, data loss, or broken deployments
✓ Task involves multiple files, services, or tools
```

### Skill File Format
```markdown
# SKILL: [Skill Name]
# Trigger: [keyword or situation that activates this skill]

## Purpose
[One sentence: what this skill does and why it exists]

## Prerequisites
- [What must exist before starting]
- [Required tools / access / environment]

## Steps
1. [First action — specific, include exact commands]
2. [Second action]
3. [...]

## Validation
- [How to confirm successful completion]
- [Expected output or state]

## Rollback
- [How to undo if something went wrong]

## Common Mistakes
- [What often goes wrong and how to avoid it]
```

### Skill File Location
```
C:\Users\USER\.cursor\rules\skills\    ← global skills (.mdc)
docs/operations/skills\                ← human-readable versions (.md)
```

### Core Skills to Build (in order)
```
Priority 1 — Build immediately:
  new-supabase-migration     how to create and apply a migration safely
  new-service-module         how to scaffold a new domain service

Priority 2 — Build in Phase 1:
  new-wp-site-provision      how to provision a WordPress site
  deploy-to-staging          staging deployment checklist

Priority 3 — Build in Phase 2:
  incident-response          what to do when something breaks
  agent-tool-expansion       how to safely expand agent tool access
```

### Skill Activation Rule
When a task matches a known skill, say:
> "This matches the [Skill Name] skill. I will follow that procedure."
Then execute the skill steps exactly. Do not improvise on established SOPs.

